And for freelancers,
for people who

00:21:19.140 --> 00:21:21.800
have extra money on the side,
it gets more complicated.

00:21:21.800 --> 00:21:23.140
Then, what goes out.

00:21:23.140 --> 00:21:26.290
So, plain and simple, you have
your obvious fixed expenses.

00:21:26.290 --> 00:21:30.040
Your rent, those sort of things,
that are clear, you know them,

00:21:30.040 --> 00:21:31.310
they're very regular.

00:21:31.310 --> 00:21:33.310
But on the other stuff,
the restaurant and bars,

00:21:33.310 --> 00:21:36.180
the travel, the shopping; that's
the stuff that people never

00:21:36.180 --> 00:21:37.700
really have a good grasp on.

00:21:37.700 --> 00:21:40.180
And so one of the
things is one, do

00:21:40.180 --> 00:21:43.030
you know that there's actually
money at the end of the month?

00:21:43.030 --> 00:21:46.360
So, if you're not tracking it,
and again, 61% of the country

00:21:46.360 --> 00:21:47.842
is living paycheck to paycheck.

00:21:47.842 --> 00:21:50.300
Which basically means they're
spending more than they make.

00:21:50.300 --> 00:21:54.600
And so, again, good people with
good incomes, that happens.

00:21:54.600 --> 00:21:56.965
So what we look at is what
comes in, what's going out,

00:21:56.965 --> 00:21:58.340
and we help you
get a real sense.

00:21:58.340 --> 00:22:00.840
And you know, LearnVest has
great trends and analysis.

00:22:00.840 --> 00:22:03.410
And at the end, we
find out what is left.

00:22:03.410 --> 00:22:05.910
We then go through this is
really good negotiation process

00:22:05.910 --> 00:22:09.860
with you where, let's just say,
your household makes $7,000

00:22:09.860 --> 00:22:12.410
a month and at the end,
there's only $1,000 left.

00:22:12.410 --> 00:22:14.810
We figure out, is there
anything else we can do?

00:22:14.810 --> 00:22:16.460
And we have great
tips in the book.

00:22:16.460 --> 00:22:19.060
And our planners
literally work and tweak,

00:22:19.060 --> 00:22:21.500
and we find a way, how do
we get $1,000 to be $2,000?

00:22:21.500 --> 00:22:24.400
Because we can get you towards
your goal so much faster.

00:22:24.400 --> 00:22:25.560
So we help you figure
out how to cut costs,

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:27.390
things you can turn
off, really great hacks.

00:22:27.390 --> 00:22:28.730
And basically, we
come up with what's

00:22:28.730 --> 00:22:30.188
the number at the
end of the month?

00:22:30.188 --> 00:22:32.300
Let's just say it's $2,000.

00:22:32.300 --> 00:22:33.760
Next.

00:22:33.760 --> 00:22:35.490
So one thing is, you
go to your budget.

00:22:35.490 --> 00:22:39.100
This is a really important
financial planning principal.

00:22:39.100 --> 00:22:42.130
So I'm a CFP, just so you
guys all know what that means.

00:22:42.130 --> 00:22:45.060
It basically means you have to
go to school for about a year.

00:22:45.060 --> 00:22:46.060
Pass many tests.

00:22:46.060 --> 00:22:49.572
You then have to take a
two day, 10 hour exam.

00:22:49.572 --> 00:22:52.030
And honestly, it's the hardest
exam I've ever been through.

00:22:52.030 --> 00:22:53.920
It's only about a 30% pass rate.

00:22:53.920 --> 00:22:56.960
It's not only extremely
broad in the topics

00:22:56.960 --> 00:22:59.570
it covers, but extremely deep.

00:22:59.570 --> 00:23:01.320
And this is one of
the best principles

00:23:01.320 --> 00:23:02.630
that I learned in it.

00:23:02.630 --> 00:23:04.127
So, I didn't make
it up, but it's

00:23:04.127 --> 00:23:06.460
one of the things that sort
of changed my life, in terms

00:23:06.460 --> 00:23:07.740
of thinking about my money.

00:23:07.740 --> 00:23:10.190
So let's just say, for
the sake of this example,

00:23:10.190 --> 00:23:13.130
that my household makes
$10,000, after taxes.

00:23:13.130 --> 00:23:14.419
That's what comes in.

00:23:14.419 --> 00:23:16.460
So when you think about
living within your means,

00:23:16.460 --> 00:23:19.150
what that really
means, is 50% or less,

00:23:19.150 --> 00:23:20.630
should go to essentials.

00:23:20.630 --> 00:23:23.120
Essential is what this
actually essential to live.

00:23:23.120 --> 00:23:25.890
It's the roof over your
head, it's your groceries,

00:23:25.890 --> 00:23:28.402
it's your utility bill, and
it's your transportation

00:23:28.402 --> 00:23:29.110
to and from work.

00:23:29.110 --> 00:23:30.770
So for you guys, you drive.

00:23:30.770 --> 00:23:33.410
So it's not just whatever
your car payment is.

00:23:33.410 --> 00:23:35.870
Your auto insurance,
and your gas.

00:23:35.870 --> 00:23:37.630
So that's what's essential.

00:23:37.630 --> 00:23:39.920
Ideally that's 50% or less.

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:42.400
One of the reasons is, if
you're a two person household,

00:23:42.400 --> 00:23:44.150
if someone lost their
job, you would still

00:23:44.150 --> 00:23:45.608
be able to maintain
your essentials

00:23:45.608 --> 00:23:47.450
without going into debt.

00:23:47.450 --> 00:23:53.210
A really important about that
50% is, of the 100, 30% or less

00:23:53.210 --> 00:23:55.180
is your rent or mortgage.

00:23:55.180 --> 00:23:57.630
So this is the one that
people get wildly wrong.

00:23:57.630 --> 00:24:00.130
And I can't tell you the number
of people that will come in,

00:24:00.130 --> 00:24:03.030
and their rent or their mortgage
is 60% of what they make.

00:24:03.030 --> 00:24:06.000
And we can see in
a 10 second window,

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.080
that you're going to
have a pretty jeopardized

00:24:08.080 --> 00:24:10.530
financial future, because
of that one decision.

00:24:10.530 --> 00:24:13.390
And I say that for
the following reason.

00:24:13.390 --> 00:24:16.361
20% is supposed to go
towards the future.

00:24:16.361 --> 00:24:17.610
And I'll walk you through why.

00:24:17.610 --> 00:24:19.570
But 20% of what you
take home every month

00:24:19.570 --> 00:24:21.779
should go to if you have
debt, paying down your debt.

00:24:21.779 --> 00:24:23.278
If you don't have
debt, contributing

00:24:23.278 --> 00:24:24.100
to your retirement.

00:24:24.100 --> 00:24:26.016
If you are already maxing
out your retirement,

00:24:26.016 --> 00:24:28.350
your next savings goal,
whatever it may be.

00:24:28.350 --> 00:24:30.580
Whether it's saving
for your kids 529 Plan,

00:24:30.580 --> 00:24:32.880
helping with some dream,
some small project

00:24:32.880 --> 00:24:35.380
you want to work on,
whatever it may be.

00:24:35.380 --> 00:24:37.534
And then, 30% is the fun stuff.

00:24:37.534 --> 00:24:38.700
That's the lifestyle budget.

00:24:38.700 --> 00:24:40.520
That's the like do you
want to go shopping?

00:24:40.520 --> 00:24:41.394
Do want to go travel?

00:24:41.394 --> 00:24:44.260
Do you want to have an
Equinox membership, etc.

00:24:44.260 --> 00:24:46.780
And one of the reasons why
people often will be like,

00:24:46.780 --> 00:24:48.580
well my rent's 60%.

00:24:48.580 --> 00:24:50.384
And we're like, well
your 20%'s gone.

00:24:50.384 --> 00:24:51.800
And the truth is,
you can't really

00:24:51.800 --> 00:24:55.010
live on your 30%
being anything--

00:24:55.010 --> 00:24:58.490
we say-- people are like,
but I can make that 10%.

00:24:58.490 --> 00:24:59.867
Well here's the problem.

00:24:59.867 --> 00:25:01.950
Every time your phone
rings, literally every time,

00:25:01.950 --> 00:25:04.100
someone's calling you to
ask you to spend money.

00:25:04.100 --> 00:25:05.570
They're calling, do you
want to go for margaritas?

00:25:05.570 --> 00:25:06.370
Do you wanna go to the gym?

00:25:06.370 --> 00:25:07.500
Do you wanna go to the game?

00:25:07.500 --> 00:25:08.450
Do you wanna meet for yoga?

00:25:08.450 --> 00:25:09.790
Do you wanna get a manicure?

00:25:09.790 --> 00:25:11.984
Your parents need
something, doesn't matter.

00:25:11.984 --> 00:25:13.400
Every time someone's
calling you ,

00:25:13.400 --> 00:25:15.700
they're asking you to do
something that requires money.

00:25:15.700 --> 00:25:18.910
And people just don't have the
willpower to always say no.

00:25:18.910 --> 00:25:21.290
That's also not a
fun life to live.

00:25:21.290 --> 00:25:23.380
And so what we find is,
if you are in a position

00:25:23.380 --> 00:25:26.910
where your rent is more than
30% of what you take home,

00:25:26.910 --> 00:25:29.630
you often end up
in a big mistake.

00:25:29.630 --> 00:25:31.390
You're not saving
enough for the future.

00:25:31.390 --> 00:25:34.350
You're in a position where
you wildly have to underspend,

00:25:34.350 --> 00:25:36.580
which is pretty difficult
for a lot of people.

00:25:36.580 --> 00:25:38.246
And so the takeaway
there is, my mentor,

00:25:38.246 --> 00:25:40.350
she's one of the early
founders of Goldman Sachs.

00:25:40.350 --> 00:25:42.500
And she's on the board of
Goldman Sachs, said to me

00:25:42.500 --> 00:25:45.480
early when we were building
LearnVest together, she goes,

00:25:45.480 --> 00:25:47.090
Alexa, the number
one thing you can

00:25:47.090 --> 00:25:49.130
do to always keep your
finances in shape,

00:25:49.130 --> 00:25:50.590
is always spend
beneath your needs

00:25:50.590 --> 00:25:51.980
in your living environment.

00:25:51.980 --> 00:25:54.370
And so if it's rent,
that's pretty clear.

00:25:54.370 --> 00:25:57.860
But for your mortgage, is
what we call PITY, principal

00:25:57.860 --> 00:25:59.981
and interest, taxes
and insurance,

00:25:59.981 --> 00:26:01.730
because those are the
four things that you

00:26:01.730 --> 00:26:04.410
must have in order to be
able to afford that home.

00:26:04.410 --> 00:26:07.340
So right now, if
you're way over 30%,

00:26:07.340 --> 00:26:09.460
we don't recommend you
go sell your house.

00:26:09.460 --> 00:26:12.360
It's just, you need to be aware
that you're actually at risk.

00:26:12.360 --> 00:26:14.746
So next.

00:26:14.746 --> 00:26:16.120
Really quickly,
on credit scores,

00:26:16.120 --> 00:26:18.286
this is one of the ones
guys, that I can't tell you,

00:26:18.286 --> 00:26:21.390
I had like almost a full
hour of questions last night

00:26:21.390 --> 00:26:21.890
about this.

00:26:21.890 --> 00:26:23.680
And it's pretty regular.

00:26:23.680 --> 00:26:25.989
Here's the takeaway, your
credit score really matters.

00:26:25.989 --> 00:26:28.030
As extremely smart, talented
people in this room,

00:26:28.030 --> 00:26:29.660
it is the only
grade that matters

00:26:29.660 --> 00:26:31.400
after you leave the
education system.

00:26:31.400 --> 00:26:32.860
And here's why it matters.

00:26:32.860 --> 00:26:34.710
So over my life, in
the next 60 years,

00:26:34.710 --> 00:26:36.750
I'm gonna buy probably
four or five homes.

00:26:36.750 --> 00:26:39.290
I'm probably also going
to like, get a nice car,

00:26:39.290 --> 00:26:41.690
start another business,
whatever it may be.

00:26:41.690 --> 00:26:43.130
Every time I go
to borrow, they're

00:26:43.130 --> 00:26:44.260
going to look at one number.

00:26:44.260 --> 00:26:46.385
They're going to be like,
what's your credit score?

00:26:46.385 --> 00:26:49.180
They'll look at your income too,
but that's basically the grade.

00:26:49.180 --> 00:26:53.060
From there, it's the difference
of 4% interest or 3% interest,

00:26:53.060 --> 00:26:55.040
based on what it looks like.

00:26:55.040 --> 00:26:59.630
Over 40 or 50 years, that
could be more than $100,000,

00:26:59.630 --> 00:27:02.120
$200,000, of saved
earnings in interest,

00:27:02.120 --> 00:27:03.690
because my credit score is good.

00:27:03.690 --> 00:27:04.402
It's that simple.

00:27:04.402 --> 00:27:06.610
And again, this is literally
why I was in Washington.

00:27:06.610 --> 00:27:09.490
I was making it so that credit
scores, and giving college kids

00:27:09.490 --> 00:27:11.170
credit cards,
should be outlawed.

00:27:11.170 --> 00:27:13.870
The average college senior
gets their credit score

00:27:13.870 --> 00:27:16.550
on like, Freshman welcome day,
with a free piece of pizza.

00:27:16.550 --> 00:27:19.015
And they graduate with
$4,000 in credit card debt.

00:27:19.015 --> 00:27:20.390
And they're already
in a position

00:27:20.390 --> 00:27:22.621
where they also have
$20,000 in student debt

00:27:22.621 --> 00:27:24.995
and they make less than that
in their first few years out

00:27:24.995 --> 00:27:25.662
of school.

00:27:25.662 --> 00:27:27.370
So as a result, it's
really hard for them

00:27:27.370 --> 00:27:28.890
to change that situation.

00:27:28.890 --> 00:27:31.040
So, credit score really matters.

00:27:31.040 --> 00:27:33.520
It ranges from 300 to 850.

00:27:33.520 --> 00:27:36.050
Everyone in this room, you
want it to be about 700.

00:27:36.050 --> 00:27:37.950
Ideally, it's above 760.

00:27:37.950 --> 00:27:39.190
That's considered excellent.

00:27:39.190 --> 00:27:40.461
That makes a big difference.

00:27:40.461 --> 00:27:41.710
And here are the three things.

00:27:41.710 --> 00:27:43.630
Only look at the top three,
because the ones at the bottom

00:27:43.630 --> 00:27:45.124
aren't even worth your time.

00:27:45.124 --> 00:27:46.290
Number one, payment history.

00:27:46.290 --> 00:27:47.340
Never miss a bill.

00:27:47.340 --> 00:27:50.630
Missing a bill knocks it about
60 points, even up to 100.

00:27:50.630 --> 00:27:54.280
And it takes literally a year,
two years, three years to fix.

00:27:54.280 --> 00:27:57.170
Something as simple as
an $86 dermatology bill.

00:27:57.170 --> 00:27:59.970
Number two, is your
credit utilization rate.

00:27:59.970 --> 00:28:01.630
So what's important
about this, and it

00:28:01.630 --> 00:28:04.262
sounds like a complicated
concept, it's not.

00:28:04.262 --> 00:28:05.970
Let's just pretend I
had one credit card,

00:28:05.970 --> 00:28:08.220
and it was $10,000,
that was my limit.

00:28:08.220 --> 00:28:11.420
So I have one credit card,
let's just say $10,000 limit.

00:28:11.420 --> 00:28:14.140
If you're carrying no debt, you
don't have to care about this.

00:28:14.140 --> 00:28:16.390
If you're carrying zero
credit card debt at all times,

00:28:16.390 --> 00:28:18.220
you always pay
your bills in full,

00:28:18.220 --> 00:28:20.740
you're at 0% for that
credit utilization.

00:28:20.740 --> 00:28:21.680
You're in good shape.

00:28:21.680 --> 00:28:23.660
If you are carrying
debt, and let's say

00:28:23.660 --> 00:28:26.350
that I'm carrying $5,000
of debt on that one credit

00:28:26.350 --> 00:28:31.800
card, that $10,000 limit, I'm
utilizing my limit at 50%.

00:28:31.800 --> 00:28:34.190
If it's above 50%,
red flags go off.

00:28:34.190 --> 00:28:37.940
So you first, want to get your
credit below 30% utilization.

00:28:37.940 --> 00:28:39.970
Which means, across
all your credit cards,

00:28:39.970 --> 00:28:42.320
you have to know what
your total limit is.

00:28:42.320 --> 00:28:44.310
But Additionally, the
takeaway, the big thing

00:28:44.310 --> 00:28:46.650
here is, just pay down your
debt as quickly as you can.

00:28:46.650 --> 00:28:50.150
That's the best way to improve
this, and it is a huge portion.

00:28:50.150 --> 00:28:52.530
